The impression left by such passages on the mind of a considerate reader is very much that which a modern author, writing without the restraint of verse, would seek to produce by a quotation or a direct reference. It is the commonplace of the art, used by a young artist: the writing at the bottom os the picture sor sear the picture should not be recognized; the tones of the master imitated by the pupil because he thinks that there is no other way os speaking correctly. Theocritus might talk generally of the Muses and of bucolic song : to Virgil the Muses must be the Muses os Sicily, and the song the song of Maenalus Even Bion ¹ and MoschuS, coming aster TheocrituS, had to appeal to Sicilian associations: how much more one not in possession of the links os sympathy imparted by a common country and common language, and an almost hereditary trans- mission of the poetical gift? And what is true of Virgil’s relation to Theocritus is true to a certain extent os his relation to Greek writers generally and to the whole body of learning which he possessed.
